  <div class="bg-white--tint  pad" id="rte">
    <section class="site-container">
      <h3 data-bk-layout="pad:trl" class="font-l">Rich-text editor / User content</h3>

      <div data-bk-layout="l:7" data-bk-links="primary fade underline" class="rte">
        <p>Rich-text content is, typically, content output by the <strong>Content Management System</strong> and written by the user in a <strong>Rich-Text Editor</strong> field. Here we tightly scope the content from the rest of the website content to reduce conflicts or the need to reset styles.</p>

        <p>Link styles are handled by a separate <a href="../links/">link scope selector</a> rather than the <code>.rte</code> class, this allows greater freedom when styling links.</p>

        <p>The goal of the <code>.rte</code> scope class is to cover as many common situations as is sensible without creating too much unused CSS. Users should not have free reign with rich-text editors otherwise they can quickly cause mayhem.</p>
      </div>

      <div data-bk-layout="l:4 l:pr:1" class="pad-b">
        <div class="alert alert--simple font-s">
          <h3 class="font-bold margin-b"><strong>Note for developers</strong></h3>

          <p>The <code>.rte</code> class sets heading styles that <em><strong>will</strong></em> override some <code>.font-*</code> classes. Keep this in mind and try to use the class only where necessary and try to wrap only the required content.</p>
        </div>
      </div>


